                This creates a local reference to an object that exists on the server.
                
                @Code(name: "YourApp.swift", file: 01-first-object-14-fetch-init.swift)
            }
            
            @Step {
                Fetch the complete object data from Parse Server.
                
                The `fetch()` method retrieves all fields for the object from the server.
                
                @Code(name: "YourApp.swift", file: 01-first-object-15-fetch.swift)
            }
            
            @Step {
                Fetch multiple objects at once using `fetchAll()`.
                
                Like `saveAll()`, this is more efficient than fetching objects individually.
                
                @Code(name: "YourApp.swift", file: 01-first-object-16-fetch-all.swift)
            }
        }
    }
    
    @Section(title: "Delete objects") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            Remove objects from Parse Server using the `delete()` method.
            
            Objects can be deleted individually or in batch operations.
        }
        
        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Create, save, and delete an object in one flow.
                
                The example shows how to create a GameScore, save it to get an objectId, and then delete it from the server.
                
                @Code(name: "YourApp.swift", file: 01-first-object-18-delete.swift)
            }
            
            @Step {
                Delete multiple objects at once using `deleteAll()`.
                
                Batch delete operations are more efficient for removing multiple objects.
                
                @Code(name: "YourApp.swift", file: 01-first-object-19-delete-all.swift)
            }
        }
    }
    
    @Section(title: "Work with advanced data types") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            Parse-Swift supports advanced data types like `ParseBytes` for binary data and `ParsePolygon` for geographic boundaries.
            
            These types must be part of your schema or you'll need the primary key to add them.
        }
        
        @Steps {
